If these criteria are met, the onsen is categorized as a radioactive spring, and many springs are labeled as “含放射能○○泉” or “含弱放射能□□泉” (e.g., “Weak Rn-Na-Cl Spring”). The highest recorded level in Japan is at the Tenmangu Spring in {{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
, with 14 Bq/L.<ref name=JBSJ />

== Usage ==
{{main|:en:Radiation hormesis#Environmental Use of Radioactive Springs}}

Radioactive spring contain trace amounts of {{ill|radium|en|Radium|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
, {{ill|radon|en|Radon|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
, {{ill|astatine|en|Astatine|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
, and other radioactive isotopes from {{ill|nuclear decay|en|Decay (radioactivity)|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
. For instance, near the source at Arima Onsen, exposure levels reach 13 μSv/h, which is comparable to levels requiring indoor sheltering under Japan's nuclear safety guidelines.

Proponents claim no adverse health effects and argue for {{ill|hormesis|en|Radiation hormesis|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} effects, asserting that radiation activates immune cells and promotes health. Critics point out potential health risks from radon exposure. Thus, radioactive springs and the hormesis theory remain subjects of both support and skepticism.

One study estimated a radiation dose of 2.8 nSv from a 2-hour bath in water containing 3.9 Bq/kg of radon. Adding 500 ml of drinking water from the spring increases the dose to 5.1 nSv. At {{ill|Masutomi Onsen|ja|増富温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
, drinking 2.2 L/day of water with 617 mBq/L radon results in an annual dose of 0.14 mSv.<ref name=JBSJ />

== Health Benefits ==
''Note: [[Health effects of hot springs|Effects]] are not guaranteed for all individuals.''

=== Indications ===
==== Bathing ====
* {{ill|General Indications for hot spring use|lt=General indications|ja|一般的適応症|1=General Indications for hot spring use|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Gout|en|Gout|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , {{ill|Hypertension|en|High blood pressure|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , {{ill|Atherosclerosis|en|Atherosclerosis|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , chronic {{ill|Skin disease|en|Skin disease|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , chronic {{ill|Gynecological diseases|en|Gynecology|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , chronic {{ill|Cholecystitis|en|Cholecystitis|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , and {{ill|Cholelithiasis|en|Gallstone|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} .
==== Drinking ====
* Gout, chronic gastrointestinal diseases, chronic cholecystitis, gallstones, {{ill|Neuralgia|en|Neuralgia|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Muscle pain|en|Myalgia|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , and joint pain.
